## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

**Q1. [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]**
*Define the BLoC pattern. List any four advantages of using BLoC for state management in Flutter.*

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**
BLoC (**Business Logic Component**) is a state management pattern that separates the presentation layer from business logic using **streams**. It receives **events** as input, processes them, and emits **states** as output.

**Four advantages** (1 mark each for any four):
1. **Separation of concerns** — UI and logic are decoupled.
2. **Testability** — Business logic can be unit-tested without UI.
3. **Predictability** — Unidirectional data flow makes state changes traceable.
4. **Reusability** — The same BLoC can be consumed by multiple widgets.
5. Scalability for large applications.
6. Reactive programming model.

---

**Q2. [KTU University Exam – June 2024]**
*Differentiate between BLoC and Cubit. State one scenario where Cubit is preferred over BLoC.*

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**

| Feature | BLoC | Cubit |
|---|---|---|
| Input | Events | Direct methods |
| Boilerplate | High | Low |
| Granularity | High | Low |
| Traceability | Excellent | Moderate |

**Scenario where Cubit is preferred** (1 mark): For **simple local state** like a toggle switch, theme switcher, or counter — where defining separate event classes adds unnecessary boilerplate. Cubit reduces code verbosity while maintaining the stream-based reactive model.

---

### Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each — Internal Choice)

---

#### **Question A (14 Marks)** [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]

**(a) [7 Marks]** Explain the core components of the BLoC pattern with a neat diagram. Describe the role of `flutter_bloc` package and list its main classes.

**(b) [7 Marks)** With a suitable Flutter code example, demonstrate how to implement a BLoC for a **login screen** that handles loading, success, and error states.

**Model Answer (a):**

The BLoC pattern has three core components:
- **Event** — A signal that something has happened (e.g., `LoginButtonPressed`).
- **State** — The resulting condition of the UI (e.g., `LoginInitial`, `LoginLoading`, `LoginSuccess`, `LoginError`).
- **BLoC** — The bridge that listens to events and emits states via a `Stream<State>`.

**Role of `flutter_bloc` package** (2 marks): It is the official Google package that provides ready-made widgets (`BlocProvider`, `BlocBuilder`, `BlocListener`, `BlocConsumer`) so developers do not manually manage `StreamSubscription`s.

**Main classes of `flutter_bloc`** (3 marks):
1. `BlocProvider` — Dependency injection.
2. `BlocBuilder` — Rebuilds UI.
3. `BlocListener` — Side effects.
4. `BlocConsumer` — Combines builder + listener.
5. `Bloc` (and `Cubit`) — Core logic classes.
6. `RepositoryProvider` — Injects repositories.

**Diagram** (1 mark): Refer to Section 4.1 of these notes.

**Model Answer (b):**

```dart
// === EVENT ===
abstract class LoginEvent extends Equatable {
  const LoginEvent();
  @override List<Object> get props => [];
}
class LoginSubmitted extends LoginEvent {
  final String email, password;
  const LoginSubmitted(this.email, this.password);
  @override List<Object> get props => [email, password];
}

// === STATE ===
abstract class LoginState extends Equatable {
  const LoginState();
  @override List<Object> get props => [];
}
class LoginInitial extends LoginState {}
class LoginLoading extends LoginState {}
class LoginSuccess extends LoginState {
  final String token;
  const LoginSuccess(this.token);
  @override List<Object> get props => [token];
}
class LoginError extends LoginState {
  final String message;
  const LoginError(this.message);
  @override List<Object> get props => [message];
}

// === BLOC ===
class LoginBloc extends Bloc<LoginEvent, LoginState> {
  final AuthRepository authRepo;
  LoginBloc(this.authRepo) : super(LoginInitial()) {
    on<LoginSubmitted>((event, emit) async {
      emit(LoginLoading());
      try {
        final token = await authRepo.login(event.email, event.password);
        emit(LoginSuccess(token));
      } catch (e) {
        emit(LoginError(e.toString()));
      }
    });
  }
}
```

```dart
// === UI ===
BlocProvider(
  create: (_) => LoginBloc(AuthRepository()),
  child: BlocConsumer<LoginBloc, LoginState>(
    listener: (ctx, state) {
      if (state is LoginError) {
        ScaffoldMessenger.of(ctx).showSnackBar(
          SnackBar(content: Text(state.message)));
      }
    },
    builder: (ctx, state) {
      if (state is LoginLoading) return CircularProgressIndicator();
      return LoginForm();
    },
  ),
);
```

**Mark distribution for (b):** Event class (2), State class (2), BLoC class (2), UI integration (1).

---

#### **Question B (14 Marks — Alternative Choice)** [KTU University Exam – June 2024]

**(a) [7 Marks]** Compare and contrast the **BLoC pattern** with the **Provider pattern** for state management in Flutter. Which is more suitable for large-scale applications and why?

**(b) [7 Marks]** Explain the `BlocObserver` class. How is it used to log all state transitions for debugging purposes? Provide a code snippet.

**Model Answer (a):**

| Feature | BLoC | Provider |
|---|---|---|
| Architecture | Event-driven, stream-based | Direct notification via `ChangeNotifier` |
| Boilerplate | High | Low |
| Testability | Excellent (pure functions) | Moderate |
| State History | Yes (event log) | No |
| Learning Curve | Steep | Gentle |
| Best For | Enterprise / large apps | Small to medium apps |

**Why BLoC is better for large-scale apps** (3 marks):
1. **Event traceability** — every UI action is a named event, making debugging and analytics easy.
2. **Strict separation** — multiple developers can work on UI and BLoC independently.
3. **Scalability** — BLoCs can be composed, and states can be sealed for exhaustive pattern matching.
4. **Built-in testability** — `bloc_test` package simplifies unit testing.
5. **Predictable state** — unidirectional flow prevents race conditions.

**Model Answer (b):**

`BlocObserver` is an abstract class in the `bloc` package that allows developers to **observe all state changes and errors** across every BLoC in the application. It is the **primary debugging tool** for BLoC-based apps (4 marks).

**Key overrideable methods:**
- `onChange(BlocBase, Change)` — called on every state change.
- `onError(BlocBase, Object, StackTrace)` — called on every error.
- `onEvent(Bloc, Event)` — called on every event added.
- `onTransition(Bloc, Transition)` — logs event → state transitions.

**Code snippet** (3 marks):

```dart
class AppBlocObserver extends BlocObserver {
  @override
  void onChange(BlocBase bloc, Change change) {
    super.onChange(bloc, change);
    print('${bloc.runtimeType} $change');
  }
  @override
  void onError(BlocBase bloc, Object error, StackTrace stack) {
    print('Error in ${bloc.runtimeType}: $error');
    super.onError(bloc, error, stack);
  }
}

void main() {
  BlocOverrides.runZoned(() => runApp(MyApp()),
      blocObserver: AppBlocObserver());
}
```

---

### 5.1 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Where KTU students lose marks on BLoC questions:**
> 1. **Writing `setState()` inside a BLoC handler** — *0 marks* awarded for state mutation logic. Always use `emit()`.
> 2. **Forgetting `Equatable`** — leads to duplicate state emissions; deduct 1 mark.
> 3. **Confusing `BlocBuilder` with `BlocListener`** — Builder rebuilds UI; Listener only triggers side effects. Mixing these is a common error.
> 4. **Not closing the BLoC** — if you write a custom BLoC without `BlocProvider`, you must call `bloc.close()` in `dispose()`. Otherwise, **2-mark penalty** for memory leak explanation.
> 5. **Missing `import 'package:flutter_bloc/flutter_bloc.dart';`** — code will not compile; evaluators deduct for incomplete snippets.
> 6. **Using `print()` for state changes** — KTU 2024 scheme expects `BlocObserver`, not `print` statements.

---

### 5.2 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rapid Revision Checklist — BLoC Pattern in Flutter**

- **BLoC = Business Logic Component**, created by **Paolo Soares** at DartConf 2018.
- Core mantra: **Events IN → States OUT**, mediated by a Stream.
- BLoC follows the formula $B : (E, S_{current}) \rightarrow S_{new}$.
- **Three core classes:** `Event`, `State`, `Bloc<Event, State>`.
- **Five main widgets from `flutter_bloc`:** `BlocProvider`, `BlocBuilder`, `BlocListener`, `BlocConsumer`, `RepositoryProvider`.
- **Cubit** is a lighter BLoC — no events, just methods calling `emit(state)`.
- Always use **immutable states** with `Equatable` and `copyWith`.
- Use `BlocObserver` for centralized logging — preferred over `print`.
- For async operations, use a **sealed/abstract state** with Loading, Success, and Error substates.
- **BLoC vs Provider:** BLoC for enterprise; Provider for small apps.
- The BLoC package is **`flutter_bloc`**, available on **pub.dev**.
- Common mistake: Never call `emit` after `bloc.close()` — causes `StateError`.
- KTU exam keyword triggers: "separate business logic", "stream-based", "unidirectional flow", "testable".
- 14-mark answers **must include a diagram** + complete code + explanation of `flutter_bloc` widgets.
- 3-mark answers should focus on **definition + advantages OR a 4-row comparison table**.

---

