# 3. Step-by-Step Implementation Walkthroughs

## 3.1 Walkthrough A — Building a Three-Screen App with Imperative Navigation

**Problem Statement**: Create a Flutter app with a Home screen displaying a list of products. Tapping a product opens a Details screen showing the product description. The Details screen has a "Buy Now" button that opens a Checkout screen.

**Step 1 — Project Scaffolding**:
```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() => runApp(const MyApp());
```

**Step 2 — App Root with Theming**:
```dart
class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyApp({super.key});
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      title: 'KTU Navigation Demo',
      theme: ThemeData(primarySwatch: Colors.indigo),
      home: const HomeScreen(),
    );
  }
}
```

**Step 3 — Home Screen with Product List**:
```dart
class HomeScreen extends StatelessWidget {
  const HomeScreen({super.key});

  final List<Map<String, String>> products = const [
    {'id': '1', 'name': 'Laptop',  'price': '₹55,000'},
    {'id': '2', 'name': 'Phone',   'price': '₹22,000'},
    {'id': '3', 'name': 'Tablet',  'price': '₹18,000'},
  ];

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: const Text('Product Catalog')),
      body: ListView.builder(
        itemCount: products.length,
        itemBuilder: (context, index) {
          final p = products[index];
          return ListTile(
            leading: const Icon(Icons.shopping_bag),
            title: Text(p['name']!),
            subtitle: Text(p['price']!),
            trailing: const Icon(Icons.arrow_forward_ios, size: 16),
            onTap: () {
              // Navigation Step A: Push with data via constructor
              Navigator.push(
                context,
                MaterialPageRoute(
                  builder: (_) => DetailsScreen(product: p),
                ),
              );
            },
          );
        },
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

**Step 4 — Details Screen Receiving Data and Navigating Forward**:
```dart
class DetailsScreen extends StatelessWidget {
  final Map<String, String> product;   // received from Home
  const DetailsScreen({super.key, required this.product});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: Text(product['name']!)),
      body: Padding(
        padding: const EdgeInsets.all(16.0),
        child: Column(
          crossAxisAlignment: CrossAxisAlignment.stretch,
          children: [
            Text('Product ID: ${product['id']}', style: const TextStyle(fontSize: 18)),
            const SizedBox(height: 8),
            Text('Price: ${product['price']}', style: const TextStyle(fontSize: 22, fontWeight: FontWeight.bold)),
            const SizedBox(height: 24),
            ElevatedButton.icon(
              icon: const Icon(Icons.payment),
              label: const Text('Buy Now'),
              onPressed: () async {
                // Navigation Step B: Push and await a result
                final orderId = await Navigator.push(
                  context,
                  MaterialPageRoute(builder: (_) => const CheckoutScreen()),
                );
                // Receive confirmation from Checkout, return to Home with toast
                if (orderId != null && context.mounted) {
                  ScaffoldMessenger.of(context).showSnackBar(
                    SnackBar(content: Text('Order placed: $orderId')),
                  );
                }
              },
            ),
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

**Step 5 — Checkout Screen Sending Data Back via `pop`**:
```dart
class CheckoutScreen extends StatelessWidget {
  const CheckoutScreen({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: const Text('Checkout')),
      body: Center(
        child: ElevatedButton(
          child: const Text('Confirm Purchase'),
          onPressed: () {
            // Return a string identifier back to DetailsScreen
            Navigator.pop(context, 'KTU2024-${DateTime.now().millisecondsSinceEpoch}');
          },
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

**Flow Trace of the Stack**:
```
Initial    : [Home]
After tap  : [Home, Details(product)]
After Buy  : [Home, Details(product), Checkout]
After pop  : [Home, Details(product)]    ←  Details receives "KTU2024-…"
After back : [Home]
```

## 3.2 Walkthrough B — Same App Refactored with Named Routes

**Step 1 — Replace `home:` with `initialRoute:` and add the `routes:` map**:
```dart
MaterialApp(
  initialRoute: '/',
  routes: {
    '/'         : (context) => const HomeScreen(),
    '/details'  : (context) => const DetailsScreen(),
    '/checkout' : (context) => const CheckoutScreen(),
  },
  onGenerateRoute: (settings) {
    // Handle data passing via RouteSettings.arguments
    if (settings.name == '/details') {
      final product = settings.arguments as Map<String, String>;
      return MaterialPageRoute(builder: (_) => DetailsScreen(product: product));
    }
    return null;   // let the static routes table handle the rest
  },
);
```

**Step 2 — Update the Home `onTap` to use `pushNamed`**:
```dart
onTap: () {
  Navigator.pushNamed(context, '/details', arguments: p);
}
```

**Step 3 — Retrieve Arguments in DetailsScreen**:
```dart
class DetailsScreen extends StatelessWidget {
  const DetailsScreen({super.key});
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    final product = ModalRoute.of(context)!.settings.arguments as Map<String, String>;
    // ... same UI as before
  }
}
```

**Step 4 — Push the Checkout via Named Route and Await the Result**:
```dart
final orderId = await Navigator.pushNamed(context, '/checkout');
```

**Step 5 — Checkout Pops with Result**:
```dart
Navigator.pop(context, 'KTU2024-${DateTime.now().millisecondsSinceEpoch}');
```

> [!NOTE]
> The **observable result** is identical to Walkthrough A — the same `Future<String?>` is returned, the same `SnackBar` fires. The difference is purely in **how** the route was located: by widget reference vs. by string identifier. KTU 14-mark answers should ideally mention *both* approaches in the "compare and contrast" sub-part.

## 3.3 Walkthrough C — Conditional Stack Manipulation with `pushAndRemoveUntil`

A classic login flow:

```dart
// After successful login, wipe the stack and present Dashboard
Navigator.pushAndRemoveUntil(
  context,
  MaterialPageRoute(builder: (_) => const DashboardScreen()),
  (route) => false,    // predicate: keep no old routes
);

// Logout: pop back to the Login screen only
Navigator.pushAndRemoveUntil(
  context,
  MaterialPageRoute(builder: (_) => const LoginScreen()),
  (route) => route.isFirst,
);
```

The lambda `(route) => false` is a `RoutePredicate` returning `true` to **keep** a route and `false` to **remove** it. Returning `false` for *all* routes empties the stack.

