### Question A (14 Marks) `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`

**(a)** Explain the `Navigator` widget in Flutter with a suitable diagram. Discuss its stack-based architecture and the significance of `MaterialPageRoute`. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a complete Flutter program to demonstrate **forward data passing** between two screens — a `LoginScreen` (with two `TextField`s for username and password, and a "Login" button) and a `WelcomeScreen` that displays *"Welcome, `<username>`!"*. Use imperative navigation. **(7 marks)**

#### Model Solution

**(a) Explanation (7 marks)**:

The `Navigator` widget is a built-in Flutter widget that manages a **stack of `Route` objects**, where each route represents a single screen or full-page dialog. When a `MaterialApp` is created, it automatically inserts a `Navigator` at the root, so any descendant widget can call `Navigator.of(context)` to access it. (2 marks)

**Stack-based architecture**:
- The stack is an ordered LIFO list. `Navigator.push()` adds a new route on top; `Navigator.pop()` removes the topmost route. The bottommost route — the `initialRoute` — is never popped via ordinary gestures. (2 marks)
- Because routes below the top are kept **alive but inactive** (offstage), their `State` objects and `ScrollController`s preserve their state across navigations, giving users a seamless "I left off exactly where I was" experience. (1 mark)

**Significance of `MaterialPageRoute`**:
- `MaterialPageRoute` is a platform-adaptive `Route` subclass that wraps the destination widget and applies the appropriate transition animation — a **fade-up** on Android, a **horizontal slide** on iOS. (1 mark)
- It also integrates with `Navigator.pop` to support system back gestures (Android predictive back) and the iOS swipe-from-edge gesture, making it the de-facto choice for screen transitions. (1 mark)

*(Attach a Mermaid or ASCII diagram of the navigator stack — see Section 4.1 for a ready template.)*

**(b) Code (7 marks)**:

