## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **High-Density Rapid-Revision Checklist** — Read this 5 minutes before the exam.

- 🔹 `Navigator` is a **stack-based** widget built into `MaterialApp`. All routes are LIFO.
- 🔹 `Navigator.push(context, MaterialPageRoute(...))` is the **imperative** form; the route is constructed inline.
- 🔹 `Navigator.pushNamed(context, '/route')` is the **declarative** form; the route is resolved via `MaterialApp.routes` or `onGenerateRoute`.
- 🔹 `RouteSettings.arguments` is the **canonical channel** for passing data when using named routes.
- 🔹 To pass data via named routes, **always** use `onGenerateRoute` (not the static `routes:` map) because the static map has no access to arguments.
- 🔹 The destination widget receives its data either through (i) its **constructor**, (ii) `ModalRoute.of(context)!.settings.arguments`, or (iii) an **InheritedWidget / Provider**.
- 🔹 **Backward** data passing is achieved with `await Navigator.push<T>()` + `Navigator.pop(context, value)`. The popped value resolves the `Future<T?>` returned by the push.
- 🔹 `Navigator.pushReplacement` swaps the top route (no back navigation to source). `Navigator.pushAndRemoveUntil(predicate)` clears routes matching the predicate.
- 🔹 `Navigator.canPop()` is a safe guard for conditional back buttons. `Navigator.maybePop()` only pops if the stack has more than one route.
- 🔹 Hot-reload preserves the `Navigator` stack, but a full app restart resets it. Plan your deep-state testing accordingly.
- 🔹 For KTU 14-mark answers, **always include a code snippet AND a flow diagram** — together they cover the "Apply" and "Visualize" Bloom levels simultaneously.
- 🔹 **Common mistakes**: missing `await`, casting `settings.arguments` to the wrong type, calling `Navigator.pop` from a context that has been disposed (use `mounted` check), and using the deprecated static `Navigator.pop()`.

