# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Networking in Flutter** refers to the process of enabling a Flutter mobile application to communicate with remote servers, web services, and Application Programming Interfaces (APIs) over standard network protocols, primarily **HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol)** and its secure variant **HTTPS**, in order to exchange structured data — most commonly in **JSON (JavaScript Object Notation)** format.

In the context of the **REST (Representational State Transfer)** architectural style, Flutter applications act as **clients** that send **HTTP requests** to server endpoints and consume **HTTP responses**. The standard CRUD operations are mapped to HTTP methods as follows:

- **C**reate → `POST`
- **R**ead → `GET`
- **U**pdate → `PUT` / `PATCH`
- **D**elete → `DELETE`

> [!NOTE]
> **Key KTU Definition:** A *RESTful API* is an API that conforms to the architectural constraints of REST, treating server-side resources as *nouns* (e.g., `/users`, `/products/42`) and HTTP methods as *verbs* (GET, POST, DELETE).

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — The "Restaurant Waiter" Model

Imagine a Flutter app is a **customer sitting at a dining table** in a restaurant:

| Restaurant Role | Flutter Equivalent |
|---|---|
| Customer | Flutter Mobile App (Client) |
| Waiter | HTTP Request (the messenger) |
| Kitchen | Remote Server / REST API |
| Order Slip (written) | HTTP Request Body (JSON) |
| Food plate returned | HTTP Response Body (JSON) |
| Receipt / Bill | HTTP Status Code (200, 404, 500…) |
| Restaurant Menu | API Endpoints (URLs) |

**The flow:**
1. The **Customer (Flutter app)** decides what to "order" — say, fetching the list of all products (`GET /products`).
2. The **Waiter (HTTP client)** carries the written order (**Request**) to the **Kitchen (Server)**.
3. The **Kitchen** prepares the food and the **Waiter** brings back the plate (**Response**) — often with a bill (**Status code**) confirming success or failure.
4. The customer **opens the box and eats the food** — analogous to **JSON Parsing** the response into usable Dart objects.

This is exactly what happens when your Flutter app calls an API like `https://fakestoreapi.com/products` — Flutter sends a `GET` request, the server returns JSON, and you parse it.

## 1.3 Standard Metrics & Constants to Remember

- **Default HTTP Port:** **80** (HTTP) and **443** (HTTPS)
- **Content-Type Header for JSON:** `application/json`
- **Typical RESTful Status Codes:**
  - **200 OK** — Successful GET
  - **201 Created** — Successful POST
  - **204 No Content** — Successful DELETE
  - **400 Bad Request** — Client-side error
  - **401 Unauthorized** — Authentication failure
  - **404 Not Found** — Resource missing
  - **500 Internal Server Error** — Server failure
- **Default JSON encoding in Flutter:** `utf-8`

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Board Tip:** Always mention the **Content-Type: application/json** header when sending JSON bodies — examiners specifically look for this in viva and written answers.
