# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 The Flutter HTTP Stack — Architecture Breakdown

Flutter does not have built-in networking for arbitrary HTTP calls in the core SDK alone; instead, it relies on **community-maintained Dart packages** that wrap the underlying OS networking layer (`dart:io` for Android/iOS/desktop, `dart:html` for web).

### 2.1.1 The `http` Package (Official Dart Team)

This is the **most commonly used package** in KTU syllabus and the de-facto standard for academic submissions.

**Step 1 — Add to `pubspec.yaml`:**

```yaml
dependencies:
  http: ^1.2.0
```

**Step 2 — Import in Dart file:**

```dart
import 'package:http/http.dart' as http;
```

> The `as http` creates a namespace alias to avoid conflicts with other `http` symbols (e.g., from `dart:io`).

**Step 3 — Anatomy of an HTTP Call:**

The `http` package exposes high-level methods that return a `Future<Response>`:

- `http.get(Uri)` → for **GET** requests
- `http.post(Uri, {headers, body})` → for **POST** requests
- `http.put(Uri, {headers, body})` → for **PUT** requests
- `http.delete(Uri, {headers})` → for **DELETE** requests

Each `Response` object contains:
- `response.statusCode` → int (e.g., 200, 404)
- `response.headers` → Map of response headers
- `response.body` → String (raw response body)
- `response.bodyBytes` → Uint8List (binary)

### 2.1.2 Async/Await Pattern in Networking

Because network calls are **I/O-bound and non-deterministic**, they must be **asynchronous**. Flutter uses Dart's `Future<T>` API and the `async/await` syntax.

```dart
Future<void> fetchData() async {
  try {
    final response = await http.get(Uri.parse('https://api.example.com/data'));
    if (response.statusCode == 200) {
      // Success — parse JSON
    } else {
      // Server returned an error status
    }
  } catch (e) {
    // Network failure / parsing error
  }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Why `async/await`?** It avoids "callback hell" and makes asynchronous code read like synchronous code, which is critical for KTU 14-mark programming questions.

## 2.2 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Syntax / Formula | Purpose / Notes |
|---|---|---|
| GET Request | `http.get(Uri.parse(url))` | Retrieve data — no body, no side-effects |
| POST Request | `http.post(Uri.parse(url), headers: {...}, body: jsonString)` | Create a new resource |
| DELETE Request | `http.delete(Uri.parse(url), headers: {...})` | Remove a resource |
| JSON Encode (Dart → String) | `jsonEncode(dartObject)` | Converts a `Map` or `List` to JSON string |
| JSON Decode (String → Dart) | `jsonDecode(jsonString)` | Returns `dynamic` — must be cast |
| URI Builder | `Uri.parse('https://api.com/users/5')` | Constructs a valid URI object |
| Future Declaration | `Future<User> getUser() async { ... }` | Marks function as asynchronous |
| Await keyword | `final data = await futureCall;` | Suspends execution until future completes |
| Status Check | `response.statusCode == 200` | Standard success indicator for GET |
| Timeout Config | `.timeout(Duration(seconds: 10))` | Prevents indefinite hanging calls |

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Pitfall:** Students often forget to wrap their network call in `try/catch`. Loss of **2 marks** is common for missing error handling.

## 2.3 Real-World Utility in Engineering

- **E-Commerce Apps** (Flipkart, Amazon clones) — `GET /products`, `POST /cart`
- **Social Media Apps** (Instagram clone) — `GET /feed`, `POST /post`, `DELETE /post/:id`
- **IoT Dashboards** — `GET /sensor-data` polled every few seconds
- **Authentication Flows** — `POST /login` with JSON credentials, receive JWT token
- **Chat Applications** — `GET /messages`, `POST /messages` (via WebSockets or REST)

In industry, Flutter apps rarely work in isolation. **Networking is the single most important skill** for a Flutter developer, and KTU 2024 Scheme has dedicated a full module to it for this reason.

## 2.4 Integrating RESTful APIs — The Bigger Picture

A complete **REST API integration** in Flutter involves four pillars:

1. **HTTP Client** — `http` package (or `dio` for advanced features)
2. **Model Class** — Dart class representing the JSON structure
3. **Service Layer** — Function that issues the HTTP call and returns parsed data
4. **State Management Hook** — `setState()`, `Provider`, `Riverpod`, or `Bloc` to update UI

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Syllabus Highlight:** KTU 2024 Scheme Module 3 explicitly asks students to "build a model class from JSON" and "perform CRUD operations via REST API." The model class is non-negotiable.
