# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Analytical Matrix — HTTP Method Decision Tree

| Need | Method | Body? | Idempotent? | Safe? | Example URL |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| Read a list | **GET** | ❌ No | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | `/api/products` |
| Read one item | **GET** | ❌ No | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | `/api/products/42` |
| Create new item | **POST** | ✅ Yes (JSON) | ❌ No | ❌ No | `/api/products` |
| Update (full) | **PUT** | ✅ Yes (JSON) | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | `/api/products/42` |
| Update (partial) | **PATCH** | ✅ Yes (JSON) | ❌ No | ❌ No | `/api/products/42` |
| Delete item | **DELETE** | ❌ No (optional) | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | `/api/products/42` |

> **Definitions to memorize for KTU:**
> - **Idempotent:** Calling the same method N times yields the same result as calling it once.
> - **Safe:** Method does not modify server state (only `GET` and `HEAD`).

## 3.2 Exhaustive Walkthrough — Building a Complete REST Integration

Let's derive a complete Flutter networking module step-by-step. We'll build a **Product Viewer** app that calls a free public API: `https://fakestoreapi.com/products`.

### Step 1 — Create the Model Class

The model class is a **blueprint** that mirrors the JSON structure returned by the server.

**Sample JSON from the API (1 product):**

```json
{
  "id": 1,
  "title": "Fjallraven - Foldsack No. 1 Backpack",
  "price": 109.95,
  "description": "Your perfect pack for everyday use...",
  "category": "men's clothing",
  "image": "https://fakestoreapi.com/img/81fPKd-2AYL._AC_SL1500_.jpg",
  "rating": {
    "rate": 3.9,
    "count": 120
  }
}
```

**Derivation logic:** The model must capture every field. For nested objects (like `rating`), we either create a separate class or use a `Map<String, dynamic>`.

**The Dart Model Class:**

```dart
class Product {
  final int id;
  final String title;
  final double price;
  final String description;
  final String category;
  final String image;
  final Rating rating;

  Product({
    required this.id,
    required this.title,
    required this.price,
    required this.description,
    required this.category,
    required this.image,
    required this.rating,
  });

  // Factory constructor — converts JSON Map to Dart object
  factory Product.fromJson(Map<String, dynamic> json) {
    return Product(
      id: json['id'] as int,
      title: json['title'] as String,
      price: (json['price'] as num).toDouble(),
      description: json['description'] as String,
      category: json['category'] as String,
      image: json['image'] as String,
      rating: Rating.fromJson(json['rating'] as Map<String, dynamic>),
    );
  }
}

class Rating {
  final double rate;
  final int count;

  Rating({required this.rate, required this.count});

  factory Rating.fromJson(Map<String, dynamic> json) {
    return Rating(
      rate: (json['rate'] as num).toDouble(),
      count: json['count'] as int,
    );
  }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Insight:** A **factory constructor** (`factory Product.fromJson`) is the standard KTU-approved way to convert JSON → Dart. It is named-from-JSON convention. Always use it.

### Step 2 — Build the API Service Layer

The service layer is a **dedicated class** that wraps HTTP calls. This is **separation of concerns** — UI never calls `http.get` directly.

```dart
import 'dart:convert';
import 'package:http/http.dart' as http;
import 'product.dart';

class ApiService {
  static const String baseUrl = 'https://fakestoreapi.com';

  // GET — Fetch all products
  Future<List<Product>> fetchProducts() async {
    final response = await http.get(Uri.parse('$baseUrl/products'));

    if (response.statusCode == 200) {
      final List<dynamic> jsonList = jsonDecode(response.body);
      return jsonList
          .map((json) => Product.fromJson(json as Map<String, dynamic>))
          .toList();
    } else {
      throw Exception('Failed to load products. Status: ${response.statusCode}');
    }
  }

  // GET — Fetch single product
  Future<Product> fetchProductById(int id) async {
    final response = await http.get(Uri.parse('$baseUrl/products/$id'));

    if (response.statusCode == 200) {
      return Product.fromJson(jsonDecode(response.body));
    } else {
      throw Exception('Product $id not found.');
    }
  }

  // POST — Create new product
  Future<Product> createProduct(Product product) async {
    final response = await http.post(
      Uri.parse('$baseUrl/products'),
      headers: {'Content-Type': 'application/json'},
      body: jsonEncode({
        'title': product.title,
        'price': product.price,
        'description': product.description,
        'category': product.category,
        'image': product.image,
      }),
    );

    if (response.statusCode == 200 || response.statusCode == 201) {
      return Product.fromJson(jsonDecode(response.body));
    } else {
      throw Exception('Failed to create product.');
    }
  }

  // DELETE — Remove a product
  Future<void> deleteProduct(int id) async {
    final response = await http.delete(Uri.parse('$baseUrl/products/$id'));

    if (response.statusCode != 200 && response.statusCode != 204) {
      throw Exception('Failed to delete product $id.');
    }
  }
}
```

### Step 3 — JSON Parsing — The Core Conversion

JSON parsing is a **two-way bridge**:

**Direction 1: JSON String → Dart Object (Decoding)**
$$\text{jsonDecode}(\text{String}) \rightarrow \text{Map<String, dynamic>} \text{ or } \text{List<dynamic>}$$

**Direction 2: Dart Object → JSON String (Encoding)**
$$\text{jsonEncode}(\text{Map} \text{ or } \text{List}) \rightarrow \text{String}$$

**The conversion math (for a single field):**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{JSON Value} &\xrightarrow{\text{jsonDecode}} \text{dynamic} \\
\text{dynamic} &\xrightarrow{\text{cast 'rate' as num}} \text{num} \\
\text{num} &\xrightarrow{\text{.toDouble()}} \text{double} \\
\text{double} &\xrightarrow{\text{assigned to model field}} \text{Dart Object Property}
\end{aligned}
$$

> **Why `(json['price'] as num).toDouble()`?** The JSON `price` field is a number, which `jsonDecode` returns as `num` (the parent of `int` and `double` in Dart). Casting directly to `double` may fail if the server sends an integer. The `num` cast handles **both** cases.

### Step 4 — Wiring It into the UI

The UI uses `FutureBuilder` to render async data declaratively.

```dart
class ProductListScreen extends StatefulWidget {
  @override
  _ProductListScreenState createState() => _ProductListScreenState();
}

class _ProductListScreenState extends State<ProductListScreen> {
  late Future<List<Product>> _productsFuture;
  final ApiService _apiService = ApiService();

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();
    _productsFuture = _apiService.fetchProducts();
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: const Text('Products')),
      body: FutureBuilder<List<Product>>(
        future: _productsFuture,
        builder: (context, snapshot) {
          if (snapshot.connectionState == ConnectionState.waiting) {
            return const Center(child: CircularProgressIndicator());
          } else if (snapshot.hasError) {
            return Center(child: Text('Error: ${snapshot.error}'));
          } else if (snapshot.hasData) {
            final products = snapshot.data!;
            return ListView.builder(
              itemCount: products.length,
              itemBuilder: (context, index) {
                final p = products[index];
                return ListTile(
                  leading: Image.network(p.image, width: 50),
                  title: Text(p.title),
                  subtitle: Text('\$${p.price}'),
                );
              },
            );
          }
          return const SizedBox.shrink();
        },
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Why `FutureBuilder`?** It is the **idiomatic Flutter widget** for consuming `Future<T>` and rebuilding UI based on the asynchronous state — `waiting`, `hasData`, `hasError`. KTU 2024 Scheme questions often require this widget.
