### **Question A (14 Marks) — [KTU University Exam – June 2024 Model Paper]**

**(a)** Explain the architecture of RESTful APIs. Compare `GET`, `POST`, and `DELETE` methods with suitable examples. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Write a complete Flutter program that uses the `http` package to perform a `GET` request to `https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users`, parses the JSON response, and displays the user names in a `ListView`. Include proper error handling and a `FutureBuilder`. **(7 Marks)**

---

#### **Model Solution:**

**(a) REST Architecture & HTTP Methods**

**REST (Representational State Transfer)** is an architectural style for designing networked applications. It treats data as **resources** identified by URIs, and uses HTTP methods to perform operations.

**Comparison Table:**

| Feature | `GET` | `POST` | `DELETE` |
|---|---|---|---|
| Purpose | Retrieve data | Create new data | Remove data |
| Idempotent | Yes | No | Yes |
| Safe | Yes | No | No |
| Request Body | None | Required (JSON) | Optional |
| Success Status | 200 OK | 201 Created | 204 No Content |
| Example URL | `/api/users/1` | `/api/users` | `/api/users/1` |

---

**(b) Complete Flutter Program**

**Step 1:** Add to `pubspec.yaml`:

```yaml
dependencies:
  flutter:
    sdk: flutter
  http: ^1.2.0
```

**Step 2:** `main.dart`:

```dart
import 'dart:convert';
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:http/http.dart' as http;

void main() => runApp(const MyApp());

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyApp({super.key});
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return const MaterialApp(home: UserListScreen());
  }
}

class UserListScreen extends StatefulWidget {
  const UserListScreen({super.key});
  @override
  _UserListScreenState createState() => _UserListScreenState();
}

class _UserListScreenState extends State<UserListScreen> {
  late Future<List<String>> _usersFuture;

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();
    _usersFuture = fetchUsers();
  }

  Future<List<String>> fetchUsers() async {
    final url = Uri.parse('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users');
    try {
      final response = await http.get(url);
      if (response.statusCode == 200) {
        final List<dynamic> data = jsonDecode(response.body);
        return data.map((user) => user['name'] as String).toList();
      } else {
        throw Exception('Failed to load users: ${response.statusCode}');
      }
    } catch (e) {
      throw Exception('Network error: $e');
    }
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: const Text('Users')),
      body: FutureBuilder<List<String>>(
        future: _usersFuture,
        builder: (context, snapshot) {
          if (snapshot.connectionState == ConnectionState.waiting) {
            return const Center(child: CircularProgressIndicator());
          } else if (snapshot.hasError) {
            return Center(child: Text('Error: ${snapshot.error}'));
          } else if (snapshot.hasData) {
            return ListView.builder(
              itemCount: snapshot.data!.length,
              itemBuilder: (context, i) =>
                  ListTile(title: Text(snapshot.data![i])),
            );
          }
          return const SizedBox.shrink();
        },
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

**Explanation of Key Lines:**

- `late Future<List<String>> _usersFuture;` — declares a Future that will hold the list of names.
- `await http.get(url);` — sends the GET request and **suspends** until response arrives.
- `jsonDecode(response.body)` — converts JSON string to Dart `List<dynamic>`.
- `user['name'] as String` — extracts each user's name and casts to `String`.
- `FutureBuilder` handles the three states: `waiting` (spinner), `hasData` (list), `hasError` (error message).

