### **Question B (14 Marks) — [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023 Model Paper]**

**(a)** Explain JSON parsing in Flutter. Differentiate between `jsonEncode()` and `jsonDecode()` with examples. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Design a Flutter application that performs a `POST` request to `https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts` with a title and body, and a `DELETE` request to remove a post with a given id. Show proper status code handling. **(7 Marks)**

---

#### **Model Solution:**

**(a) JSON Parsing in Flutter**

JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is a **lightweight, text-based data interchange format** that is the de-facto standard for REST APIs. Flutter provides two key functions in the `dart:convert` library:

| Function | Direction | Input | Output | Use Case |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `jsonDecode()` | String → Dart | `String` | `dynamic` (`Map` or `List`) | Parsing server response |
| `jsonEncode()` | Dart → String | `Map` / `List` | `String` | Building request body |

**Example:**

```dart
import 'dart:convert';

// Encoding
Map<String, dynamic> user = {'name': 'Alice', 'age': 25};
String jsonStr = jsonEncode(user);
// Result: '{"name":"Alice","age":25}'

// Decoding
String serverResponse = '{"name":"Bob","age":30}';
Map<String, dynamic> data = jsonDecode(serverResponse);
print(data['name']); // Bob
```

**Important:** `jsonDecode` returns `dynamic`, so explicit type casting is mandatory — e.g., `data['age'] as int`.

---

**(b) POST and DELETE Implementation**

```dart
import 'dart:convert';
import 'package:http/http.dart' as http;

class PostService {
  static const String baseUrl = 'https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts';

  // POST — Create a new post
  Future<Map<String, dynamic>> createPost(String title, String body) async {
    final response = await http.post(
      Uri.parse(baseUrl),
      headers: {'Content-Type': 'application/json'},
      body: jsonEncode({'title': title, 'body': body, 'userId': 1}),
    );

    if (response.statusCode == 201) {
      return jsonDecode(response.body) as Map<String, dynamic>;
    } else {
      throw Exception('POST failed with status: ${response.statusCode}');
    }
  }

  // DELETE — Remove a post by id
  Future<bool> deletePost(int id) async {
    final response = await http.delete(Uri.parse('$baseUrl/$id'));

    if (response.statusCode == 200 || response.statusCode == 204) {
      return true;
    } else {
      throw Exception('DELETE failed with status: ${response.statusCode}');
    }
  }
}
```

**Key Points for Valuation:**

- **POST** must include the `Content-Type: application/json` header and a `body` parameter — **2 marks**.
- **POST** expects status **201 Created** on success — **1 mark**.
- **DELETE** typically returns **200 OK** or **204 No Content** — handling both is good practice — **1 mark**.
- Error throwing with descriptive messages — **1 mark**.
- Proper use of `async/await` — **1 mark**.

