# 📘 SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Exhaustive Walkthrough: Transforming `.then()` Chains into `async`/`await`

This is the **most common KTU exam transformation**. We will convert a chained Future pipeline into its equivalent `async`/`await` form, step by step.

### 3.1.1 Given: Callback-Style (`.then()` chain)

```dart
// ORIGINAL: .then() chain style
void getUserProfile(int userId) {
  fetchUser(userId)
      .then((user) {
        print('Step 1: Got user $user');
        return fetchPosts(user.id);
      })
      .then((posts) {
        print('Step 2: Got ${posts.length} posts');
        return fetchComments(posts.first.id);
      })
      .then((comments) {
        print('Step 3: Got ${comments.length} comments');
      })
      .catchError((e) {
        print('Error: $e');
      })
      .whenComplete(() {
        print('All done!');
      });
}
```

### 3.1.2 Step-by-Step Transformation to `async`/`await`

**Step 1 — Mark the function as `async` and change return type to `Future<void>`.**

```dart
Future<void> getUserProfile(int userId) async {
```

*Reason:* The function now contains `await`, so it must be `async`. The original was `void` (fire-and-forget), so we change to `Future<void>`.

**Step 2 — Replace each `.then((x) { ...; return y; })` with `final x = await ...;`.**

```dart
Future<void> getUserProfile(int userId) async {
  final user = await fetchUser(userId);
  print('Step 1: Got user $user');
  final posts = await fetchPosts(user.id);
  print('Step 2: Got ${posts.length} posts');
  final comments = await fetchComments(posts.first.id);
  print('Step 3: Got ${comments.length} comments');
}
```

*Reason:* `await fetchUser(userId)` does *exactly* what `.then((user) => ...)` does — it pauses until the Future completes and binds the value to `user`. The implicit `return` is replaced by sequential `await`s.

**Step 3 — Replace `.catchError` with a `try`/`catch` block.**

```dart
Future<void> getUserProfile(int userId) async {
  try {
    final user = await fetchUser(userId);
    print('Step 1: Got user $user');
    final posts = await fetchPosts(user.id);
    print('Step 2: Got ${posts.length} posts');
    final comments = await fetchComments(posts.first.id);
    print('Step 3: Got ${comments.length} comments');
  } catch (e) {
    print('Error: $e');
  }
}
```

*Reason:* `await` automatically *re-throws* errors into the surrounding `try`/`catch`. This is more idiomatic Dart and matches Java/C++ syntax familiar to KTU students.

**Step 4 — Replace `.whenComplete` with a `finally` block.**

```dart
Future<void> getUserProfile(int userId) async {
  try {
    final user = await fetchUser(userId);
    final posts = await fetchPosts(user.id);
    final comments = await fetchComments(posts.first.id);
  } catch (e) {
    print('Error: $e');
  } finally {
    print('All done!');
  }
}
```

### 3.1.3 Final Equivalent Code

```dart
Future<void> getUserProfile(int userId) async {
  try {
    final user = await fetchUser(userId);
    print('Step 1: Got user $user');
    final posts = await fetchPosts(user.id);
    print('Step 2: Got ${posts.length} posts');
    final comments = await fetchComments(posts.first.id);
    print('Step 3: Got ${comments.length} comments');
  } catch (e) {
    print('Error: $e');
  } finally {
    print('All done!');
  }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Insight:** The compiler internally desugars this back into a `.then()` chain. The two styles are **semantically equivalent**; `async`/`await` is purely a **readability enhancement**.

---

## 3.2 Exhaustive Walkthrough: Building a Custom Stream with StreamController

This is the classic "**Live Counter**" derivation — a KTU favorite.

### 3.2.1 Requirement

Build a Stream that emits `1, 2, 3` every second, then closes and prints a final message.

### 3.2.2 Step-by-Step Construction

**Step 1 — Create a `StreamController`.**

```dart
final controller = StreamController<int>();
```

*Logic:* The `StreamController<int>` indicates the Stream will emit `int` values. By default, it is a **single-subscription** stream.

**Step 2 — Schedule periodic emissions using a `Timer`.**

```dart
int counter = 0;
Timer.periodic(Duration(seconds: 1), (timer) {
  counter++;
  controller.add(counter);     // Pushes value into the stream
  if (counter == 3) {
    timer.cancel();            // Stop the timer
    controller.close();        // Close the stream → triggers onDone
  }
});
```

*Logic:* Every 1 second, increment `counter` and call `controller.add(counter)`. When `counter == 3`, cancel the timer and close the controller.

**Step 3 — Listen to the Stream.**

```dart
controller.stream.listen(
  (value) => print('Received: $value'),
  onError: (e) => print('Error: $e'),
  onDone: () => print('Stream finished!'),
);
```

**Step 4 — (Optional) Use `await for` for cleaner consumption.**

```dart
Future<void> consumeStream() async {
  await for (final value in controller.stream) {
    print('Received: $value');
  }
  print('Stream finished!');
}
```

### 3.2.3 Expected Output

```
Received: 1
Received: 2
Received: 3
Stream finished!
```

### 3.2.4 Analytical Trace Table

| Time (s) | `counter` | Action | Stream State |
|---|---|---|---|
| 0.0 | 0 | Stream created | Open (no data) |
| 1.0 | 1 | `add(1)` | Emits `1` to listener |
| 2.0 | 2 | `add(2)` | Emits `2` to listener |
| 3.0 | 3 | `add(3)` + `close()` | Emits `3`, then `onDone` fires |

---

## 3.3 Analytical Matrix: When to Use What

| Scenario | Best Choice | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| Fetch a single REST API response | `Future` + `await` | One result, then stop |
| Listen to real-time Firestore updates | `Stream` + `listen` | Continuous updates |
| Read a file from disk once | `Future<File>` | Single read operation |
| Track user typing in a search box | `Stream<String>` | Many keystrokes over time |
| Show a snackbar after a button press | `Future<void>` | One-shot side effect |
| Stream sensor data to multiple widgets | **Broadcast** `Stream` | Multiple subscribers needed |
| Combine 3 API calls in parallel | `Future.wait([...])` | Independent async ops |
| Iterate a Stream inside a Bloc/Cubit | `await for` | Cleanest event handling |

---

## 3.4 Exhaustive Code: `Future.wait` for Parallel Async Calls

**Use Case:** Fetch user, posts, and notifications **in parallel** (not sequentially).

```dart
Future<void> loadDashboardParallel() async {
  try {
    final results = await Future.wait([
      fetchUser(),       // Future<User>
      fetchPosts(),      // Future<List<Post>>
      fetchNotifications() // Future<List<Notification>>
    ]);
    final user = results[0] as User;
    final posts = results[1] as List<Post>;
    final notifs = results[2] as List<Notification>;
    print('Loaded ${posts.length} posts and ${notifs.length} notifications for ${user.name}');
  } catch (e) {
    print('One of the calls failed: $e');
  }
}
```

*Logic:* `Future.wait` starts all three Futures **simultaneously** and resolves when **all** complete. If *any* one throws, the entire `wait` rejects with that error (short-circuit behavior).

> [!WARNING]
> **Common KTU Mistake:** Students often write `await fetchUser(); await fetchPosts();` sequentially, taking 3× longer. Use `Future.wait` for **independent** operations.

---

## 3.5 Exhaustive Code: Error Propagation in Async Functions

```dart
Future<int> divideAsync(int a, int b) async {
  if (b == 0) {
    throw ArgumentError('Division by zero');  // Becomes a Future error
  }
  return a ~/ b;  // Automatically wrapped in Future<int>
}

Future<void> caller() async {
  try {
    final result = await divideAsync(10, 0);
    print(result);
  } on ArgumentError catch (e) {  // Type-specific catch
    print('Caught ArgumentError: $e');
  } catch (e) {  // Generic catch
    print('Caught generic error: $e');
  }
}
```

*Logic:* The `throw` inside an `async` function automatically becomes a `Future` error. The caller uses `await` and wraps it in `try`/`catch`. This is the idiomatic Dart pattern — preferred over `.catchError()` in modern code.
