# 📘 SECTION 4: Structural Diagrams & Schematics

## 4.1 Diagram 1: Future Lifecycle State Machine

This diagram shows how a `Future` transitions from creation to completion.

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Uncompleted: Future<int> created
    Uncompleted --> CompletedWithData: async op succeeds\n(value emitted)
    Uncompleted --> CompletedWithError: async op fails\n(error thrown)
    CompletedWithData --> [*]: then() / await resumes
    CompletedWithError --> [*]: catchError / try-catch resumes
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Reading the diagram:** Every `Future` begins in the *Uncompleted* state. It then transitions **exactly once** to either *CompletedWithData* or *CompletedWithError* — never both, never back. This immutability is what makes Futures safe to pass around.

---

## 4.2 Diagram 2: The Dart Event Loop with Microtask & Event Queues

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Main Function Entry] --> B[Execute sync code top-to-bottom]
    B --> C{Event Loop Iteration}
    C --> D[Microtask Queue]
    D --> E{Any microtasks pending?}
    E -- Yes --> F[Run ALL microtasks\nin FIFO order]
    F --> E
    E -- No --> G[Event Queue]
    G --> H{Take next event}
    H --> I[Run event handler\ne.g. Timer, I/O, Gesture]
    I --> J[Render frame if needed]
    J --> C
    I -.adds microtask.-> D
    H -.Future.then callback.-> D
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Key takeaway:** When you call `Future.then(callback)`, the `callback` is enqueued as a **microtask**, not an event. This is why chained `.then()` callbacks run *before* the next `Future.delayed(Duration.zero)` event.

---

## 4.3 Diagram 3: Future.then() vs async/await Equivalence

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    subgraph A["Style 1: .then() chain"]
        A1[fetchUser] -- then user --> A2[fetchPosts]
        A2 -- then posts --> A3[fetchComments]
        A1 -.catchError.-> AErr[Handle Error]
    end

    subgraph B["Style 2: async/await (equivalent)"]
        B1[await fetchUser] --> B2[await fetchPosts]
        B2 --> B3[await fetchComments]
        B1 -.try/catch.-> BErr[Handle Error]
    end
```

> [!NOTE]
> The two boxes produce **identical** execution order. `async`/`await` is purely a **syntactic transformation** done by the compiler.

