### 🔹 Core Concepts
- [ ] Dart is **single-threaded** with one **Event Loop** and two queues: **Microtask** (priority) and **Event** (lower).
- [ ] **`Future<T>`** = single async result; completes once with data **or** error (never both).
- [ ] **`async`** keyword marks a function as asynchronous; return type auto-wraps in `Future`.
- [ ] **`await`** pauses the local async function only; the Event Loop keeps running → UI stays responsive.
- [ ] **`Stream<T>`** = sequence of async events; can emit zero, one, or many values.
- [ ] **`StreamController`** is the manual "faucet" — you call `add()` to push, `close()` to end.
- [ ] **Single-subscription** streams allow **one** listener; **broadcast** streams allow **many**.
- [ ] **`.then()`** chains and **`async`/`await`** are **semantically equivalent** — compiler desugars one into the other.
- [ ] **`try`/`catch`/`finally`** is the idiomatic error-handling pattern in `async`/`await` code.
- [ ] **`Future.wait([...])`** runs independent async operations **in parallel**.

