## 3. Step-by-Step Walkthroughs, Code Derivations & Analytical Matrix

> [!NOTE]
> For a programming-oriented topic like Flutter Testing, the "derivation" is the **step-by-step construction of test code and debugging logic**. Every code block below is exhaustive, runnable, and annotated.

### 3.1 Derivation: Writing a Unit Test (Step-by-Step)

**Scenario:** We test a pure function `calculateTotal(price, qty)` that must return `price * qty`.

**Step 1 — Project initialization.** Create a Flutter project. By default, Flutter generates a `test/widget_test.dart`. Add a new file `test/calc_test.dart`.

**Step 2 — Implement the function-under-test** in `lib/calculator.dart`:

```dart
// lib/calculator.dart
class Calculator {
  static double calculateTotal(double price, int quantity) {
    if (price < 0 || quantity < 0) {
      throw ArgumentError('Price and quantity must be non-negative');
    }
    return price * quantity;
  }
}
```

**Step 3 — Write the unit test** in `test/calculator_test.dart`:

```dart
// test/calculator_test.dart
import 'package:flutter_test/flutter_test.dart';
import 'package:my_app/calculator.dart';

void main() {
  // ----- AAA Pattern: Arrange, Act, Assert -----

  test('calculateTotal returns correct product for valid inputs', () {
    // Arrange
    const double price = 50.0;
    const int quantity = 3;

    // Act
    final double result = Calculator.calculateTotal(price, quantity);

    // Assert
    expect(result, equals(150.0));
  });

  test('calculateTotal returns 0.0 when quantity is 0', () {
    // Arrange
    const double price = 99.99;
    const int quantity = 0;

    // Act
    final double result = Calculator.calculateTotal(price, quantity);

    // Assert
    expect(result, equals(0.0));
  });

  test('calculateTotal throws ArgumentError on negative price', () {
    // Arrange
    const double price = -10.0;
    const int quantity = 2;

    // Act & Assert
    expect(
      () => Calculator.calculateTotal(price, quantity),
      throwsA(isA<ArgumentError>()),
    );
  });
}
```

**Step 4 — Run the test:**

```bash
flutter test test/calculator_test.dart
```

**Step 5 — Interpret the output:**

```
+00:01 - calculateTotal returns correct product for valid inputs
+00:01 - calculateTotal returns 0.0 when quantity is 0
+00:01 - calculateTotal throws ArgumentError on negative price
All tests passed!
```

**Why each step matters (Explanation):**
- **Arrange** isolates inputs, making the test deterministic.
- **Act** performs a *single* operation — never chain multiple actions in a unit test.
- **Assert** uses `expect()` with precise matchers; vague assertions hide bugs.
- **Negative tests** (Step 3, third test) are as important as happy-path tests.

### 3.2 Derivation: Writing a Widget Test (Step-by-Step)

**Scenario:** Verify a `LoginButton` widget disables itself when tapped and shows a spinner.

**Step 1 — Create the widget-under-test** in `lib/login_button.dart`:

```dart
// lib/login_button.dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

class LoginButton extends StatefulWidget {
  const LoginButton({super.key});

  @override
  State<LoginButton> createState() => _LoginButtonState();
}

class _LoginButtonState extends State<LoginButton> {
  bool _isLoading = false;

  void _onPressed() {
    setState(() => _isLoading = true);
    // Simulate async auth call
    Future.delayed(const Duration(seconds: 2), () {
      if (mounted) setState(() => _isLoading = false);
    });
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return ElevatedButton(
      onPressed: _isLoading ? null : _onPressed,
      child: _isLoading
          ? const SizedBox(
              width: 16,
              height: 16,
              child: CircularProgressIndicator(strokeWidth: 2),
            )
          : const Text('Login'),
    );
  }
}
```

**Step 2 — Write the widget test** in `test/login_button_test.dart`:

```dart
// test/login_button_test.dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:flutter_test/flutter_test.dart';
import 'package:my_app/login_button.dart';

void main() {
  testWidgets('LoginButton starts with "Login" text and enabled',
      (WidgetTester tester) async {
    // Arrange: pump the widget into the test harness
    await tester.pumpWidget(
      const MaterialApp(home: Scaffold(body: LoginButton())),
    );

    // Assert: initial state
    expect(find.text('Login'), findsOneWidget);
    expect(find.byType(CircularProgressIndicator), findsNothing);

    final ElevatedButton button = tester.widget(find.byType(ElevatedButton));
    expect(button.onPressed, isNotNull);
  });

  testWidgets('Tapping LoginButton shows spinner and disables button',
      (WidgetTester tester) async {
    // Arrange
    await tester.pumpWidget(
      const MaterialApp(home: Scaffold(body: LoginButton())),
    );

    // Act: simulate user tap
    await tester.tap(find.byType(ElevatedButton));
    await tester.pump(); // Trigger setState rebuild

    // Assert: loading state
    expect(find.byType(CircularProgressIndicator), findsOneWidget);
    expect(find.text('Login'), findsNothing);

    final ElevatedButton button = tester.widget(find.byType(ElevatedButton));
    expect(button.onPressed, isNull);
  });
}
```

**Step 3 — Run the widget test:**

```bash
flutter test test/login_button_test.dart
```

**Explanation of `tester.pump()` mechanics:**

$$ \text{pump}() \Rightarrow \text{Advance by 1 frame} \approx 16.67 \text{ ms at 60fps} $$

$$ \text{pump}(\Delta t) \Rightarrow \text{Advance by } \Delta t \text{, useful for animations} $$

- `pump()` rebuilds the widget tree once — sufficient for synchronous `setState`.
- `pumpAndSettle()` repeatedly pumps until no further frames are scheduled — used to wait for animations to complete.
- `pump(Duration(seconds: 1))` simulates elapsed time without blocking the test.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Pitfall:** Forgetting to call `tester.pump()` after `setState` is the #1 reason widget tests fail. The framework doesn't auto-rebuild in test mode.

### 3.3 Derivation: Writing an Integration Test (Step-by-Step)

**Step 1 — Add dependency** in `pubspec.yaml`:

```yaml
dev_dependencies:
  integration_test:
    sdk: flutter
```

**Step 2 — Create** `integration_test/app_test.dart`:

```dart
// integration_test/app_test.dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:flutter_test/flutter_test.dart';
import 'package:integration_test/integration_test.dart';
import 'package:my_app/main.dart';

void main() {
  IntegrationTestWidgetsFlutterBinding.ensureInitialized();

  testWidgets('Full login flow on real device', (WidgetTester tester) async {
    // Arrange
    await tester.pumpWidget(const MyApp());

    // Act 1: find email field and enter text
    await tester.enterText(find.byKey(const Key('email_field')), 'user@test.com');
    await tester.enterText(find.byKey(const Key('password_field')), 'pass1234');
    await tester.tap(find.byKey(const Key('login_button')));
    await tester.pumpAndSettle(const Duration(seconds: 5));

    // Assert: dashboard appears
    expect(find.text('Welcome'), findsOneWidget);
  });
}
```

**Step 3 — Run on a connected device:**

```bash
flutter test integration_test/app_test.dart -d <device-id>
```

**Why this differs from widget testing (Explanation):**
- The test runs in a *real* app process on the *real* device — true platform plugins (camera, GPS, biometrics) work.
- `pumpAndSettle()` waits for **all** async work including network calls.
- Slower, but verifies the entire stack: Dart ⇄ Flutter ⇄ Engine ⇄ OS.

### 3.4 Derivation: Debugging Workflow (Step-by-Step)

**Step-by-step debug procedure using VS Code + Dart DevTools:**

| Step | Action | Tool / Shortcut | Purpose |
|:---:|:---|:---|:---|
| 1 | Insert breakpoint at suspected line | Click gutter in VS Code | Pause execution |
| 2 | Run app in **Debug mode** | F5 (VS Code) | Start debugger |
| 3 | App pauses at breakpoint | IDE highlights line | Freeze state for inspection |
| 4 | Inspect variables in **Debug panel** | Hover or watch panel | Read live values |
| 5 | Step over (`F10`) / Step into (`F11`) | Keyboard | Trace logic flow |
| 6 | Continue (`F5`) | Keyboard | Resume until next breakpoint |
| 7 | Open **Dart DevTools** | Click "Open DevTools" in debug toolbar | Deep inspection |
| 8 | Inspect **Widget Inspector tab** | DevTools → Widget Inspector | Visualize widget tree |
| 9 | Inspect **Memory tab** | DevTools → Memory | Find memory leaks |
| 10 | Inspect **Timeline tab** | DevTools → Timeline | Profile UI performance |
| 11 | Inspect **Network tab** | DevTools → Network | Trace HTTP calls |
| 12 | Inspect **Logging tab** | DevTools → Logging | Filter log messages |

**Mathematical model of debugging efficiency (analytical insight):**

$$ \text{Debug Time} \approx \frac{\text{Defect Location Difficulty}}{\text{Tool Precision}} \times \text{Codebase Size} $$

Where *Tool Precision* increases in the order: `print` < `breakpoints` < **DevTools** < **Profiler**.

### 3.5 Analytical Matrix: When to Use Which Test

| Scenario | Recommended Test | Justification |
|:---|:---|:---|
| Validate a tax calculation function | **Unit** | Pure logic, no UI |
| Verify a form submits correctly | **Widget** | UI interaction in isolation |
| Test login → dashboard flow with real API | **Integration** | End-to-end, native + network |
| Validate a `Bloc`/`Provider` state transition | **Unit** (with mocks) | Logic, no rendering needed |
| Check layout on different screen sizes | **Widget** + golden tests | Render-only concern |
| Performance test (60fps scrolling) | **Integration** + Profile mode | Real device + timeline |
| Database CRUD | **Unit** with mock DB | Isolated logic |
| Push notification handling | **Integration** | Native plugin behavior |

